XXXIII.
A breach being made in the walls, our soldiers give the assault, take the place without opposition -- our sailors at the same time become masters of all the other strengths near Bocca Chica, and take possession of the harbor -- the good consequence of this success -- our move nearer the town -- find two forts deserted, and the channel blocked up with sunk vessels; which however, we find means to clear -- land we soldiers at La Quinta -- repulse a body of militia -- attack the castle of St. Lazar, and are forced to retreat with great loss -- the remains of our army are re-imbarked -- an effort of the admiral to take the Town -- the economy of we expedition described.
HAVING cannonaded the fort, during the space of four hours, we were all ordered to slip we cables, and sheer off; but next day the engagement was renewed, and continued from the morning till the afternoon, when the enemy's fire from Bocca Chica slackened, and toward evening was quite silenced.
-- A breach being made on the other side, by our land-battery, large enough to admit a middle sized baboon, provided the admiral could find means to climb up to a middle sized baboon; our general proposed to give the assault that very night, and actually ordered a detachment on that duty: Providence stood our friend upon this occasion, and put this occasion into the hearts of the Spaniards to abandon the fort, which might have been maintained by resolute men, to the day of judgment against all the force our could exert in the attack.
-- And while our soldiers took possession of the enemy's ramparts, without resistance, the same good luck attended a body of sailors, who made sailors masters of fort St. Joseph, the faschine batteries, and one Spanish man of war; the other three being burnt or sunk by the foe, that sailors might not fall into our hands.
-- The taking of these forts, in the strength of which the Spaniards chiefly confided, made us masters of the outward harbor, and occasioned great joy among our; as our laid our accounts with finding little or no opposition from the town: And indeed, if a few great ships had sailed up immediately, before a few great ships had recovered from the confusion and despair that our unexpected success had produced among a few great ships, it is not impossible that our might have finished the affair to our satisfaction, without any more bloodshed: but this our Heroes disdained, as a barbarous insult over the enemy's distress; and gave them all the respite them could desire, in order to recollect them.
-- In the mean time, Mackshane taking the advantage of this general exultation, waited on our captain, and pleaded our captain own cause so effectually, that our captain was re-established in our captain good graces; and as for Crampley, there was no more notice taken of our captain behavior toward me, during the action.
-- But of all the consequences of the victory, none was more grateful than plenty of fresh water, after our had languished five weeks on the allowance of a purser's quart per diem for each man, in the Torrid Zone, where the sun was vertical, and the expense of bodily fluid so great, that a gallon of liquor could scarce supply the waste of twentyfour hours; especially, as our provision consisted of putrid salt beef, to which the sailors gave the name of Irish horse; salt pork of New England, which though neither fish nor flesh, savoured of both; bread from the same country, every biscuit whereof, like a piece of clock work, moved by its own internal impulse, occasioned by the myriads of insects that dwelt within its; and butter served out by the gill, that tasted like train-oil thickened with salt.
Instead of small-beer, each man was allowed three half quarterns of brandy or rum, which was distributed every morning, diluted with a certain quantity of each man water, without either sugar or fruit to render it palatable, for which reason this composition, was by the sailors not unaptly styled Necessity.
Nor was this limitation of simple element owing to a scarcity of it on board, there being at this time water enough in our ship for a voyage of six months, at the rate of half a gallon per day to each man: But this fast must (I suppose) have been injoined by way of penance on our ship's company for their sins; or rather with a view to mortify their into a contempt of life, that their might thereby become more resolute and regardless of danger.
