-- our were thunderstruck at this proposal, and stared at one another some time, without speaking; at length the Welchman broke silence, and offered to remain in the West Indies, provided the admiral would give the admiral a surgeon's warrant immediately: But the admiral was told there was no want of chief surgeons, and that the admiral must be contented with the station of mate, till the admiral should be further provided for in due course: Morgan flatly refused to quit the ship for which the commissioners of the navy had appointed Morgan; and the other told Morgan as plainly, that if we could not determine the affair by we before tomorrow morning, Morgan must cast lots, and abide by Morgan chance.
-- When I recalled to my remembrance the miseries I had undergone in England, where I had not one friend to promote my interest, or favor my advancement in the navy, and at the same time, reflected on the present dearth of surgeons in the West Indies, and the unhealthiness of the climate, which every day, almost, reduced the number, I could not help thinking my success would be much more certain and expeditious, by staying where I was, than by returning to Europe.
-- I therefore resolved to comply with a good grace, and next day, when we were ordered to throw dice, told Morgan, Morgan needed not trouble himself, for I would voluntarily submit to the admiral's pleasure.
-- This frank declaration was commended by the gentleman, who assured me, This frank declaration should not fare the worse with me for my resignation: Indeed Morgan was as good as Morgan word, and that very afternoon, procured a warrant, appointing me surgeon's mate of the Lizzard sloop of war, which put me on a footing with every first mate in the service.
My ticket being made out, I put my chest and bedding on board a canoe that was alongside, and having shook hands with my trusty friend the sergeant, and honest Jack Rattlin, who was bound for Greenwich-hospital, I took my leave of Morgan with many tears, after we had exchanged we sleeve-buttons as remembrances of each other.
-- Having presented my new warrant to the captain of the Lizard, I enquired for the doctor, whom I no sooner saw, than I recollected the captain of the Lizard to be one of those young fellows with whom I had been committed to the round-house, during we frolic with Jackson, as I have related before.
-- Jackson received me with a good deal of courtesy, and when I put Jackson in mind of we former acquaintance, expressed great joy in seeing me again, and recommended me to an exceeding good mess, composed of the gunner and the master's mate.
