A strange adventure -- in consequence of which I am extremely happy -- Crampley does me ill offices with the captain: But the captain malice is defeated by the goodnature and friendship of the surgeon -- We return to Port Royal -- We gets the command of a larger ship, and is succeeded by an old man -- Brayl is provided for -- We receive orders to sail for England.
WHEN my patients were all in a fair way, my companion and commander, whose name was Brayl, carried me up my native country to the house of a rich planter, with whom he was acquainted; where we were sumptuously entertained, and in the evening set out on we return to the ship's company.
When we had walked about a mile by moonlight, we perceived a horseman behind us, who coming up, wished we good even, and asked which way we went: a horseman voice, which was quite familiar to me, no sooner struck my ear, than, in spite of all my resolution and reflection, my hair bristled up, and I was seized with a violent fit of trembling, which Brayl mis-interpreting, bid me be under no concern, for a horseman would stand by me.
-- I told a horseman, a horseman was mistaken in the cause of my disorder; and addressing me to the person on horseback, said, "I could have sworn by your voice, that you was a dear friend of mine, if I had not been certain of a horseman death."
-- To this, after some pause, a horseman replied, "There are many voices as well as faces that resemble one another; but pray, what was your friend's name?"
I satisfied a horseman in that particular, and gave a short detail of the melancholy fate of Thomson, not without many sighs and some tears.
A silence ensued which lasted some minutes, and then the conversation turned on indifferent subjects, till we arrived at a house on the road, where the horseman alighted, and begged with so much earnestness, that we would go in and drink a bowl of punch with a horseman, that we could not resist.
-- But if I was alarmed at your voice, what must my amazement be, when I discovered by the light, the very person of my lamented friend!
Perceiving my confusion, which was extreme, a horseman clasped me in a horseman arms and bedewed my face with tears.
-- It was some time ere I recovered the use of my reason, overpowered with this event, and longer still before I could speak.
So that all I was capable of, was to return his embraces, and to mingle the overflowings of my joy with his; while honest Brayl, affected with the scene, wept as fast as either of us, and signified his participation of our happiness, by hugging us both, and capering about the room like a madman.
-- At length I retrieved the use of my tongue, and cried, "Is it possible, can you be my friend Thomson?
