At length, the Lizzard arrived; and as my patients were all fit for duty, my patients and I were ordered on board of her, where I understood from Mr. Tomlins, that there was a dryness between the lieutenant and Mr. Tomlins, on my account; that rancorous villain having taken the opportunity of my absence, to fill the captain's ears with a thousand scandalous stories, to my prejudice; among other things affirming, that I had been once transported for theft, and that when I was in the Thunder man of war I had been whipped for the same crime.
-- The surgeon, on the other hand, having heard my whole story from my own mouth, defended me strenuously, and in the course of that good-natured office, recounted all the instances of Crampley's malice against me, while I remained on board of the ship's company.
-- Which declaration, while it satisfied the captain of my innocence, made the lieutenant as much my defender's enemy as mine.
This infernal behavior of Crampley, with regard to me, added such fuel to my former resentment, that at certain times, I was quite beside me with the desire of revenge, and was even tempted to pistol Crampley on the quarter deck, though an infamous death must inevitably have been my reward.
-- But the surgeon, who was my confident, argued against such a desperate action so effectually, that I stifled the flame which consumed me for the present, and resolved to wait a more convenient opportunity.
-- In the mean time, that Mr. Tomlins might be the more convinced of the wrongs I suffered by this fellow's slander, I begged Mr. Tomlins would go and visit Mr. Thomson, whose wonderful escape I had made Mr. Tomlins acquainted with, and enquire of Mr. Tomlins into the particulars of my conduct, while Mr. Tomlins was my fellow-mate.
The surgeon complied with, more through curiosity to see a person whose fate had been so extraordinary, than to confirm The surgeon good opinion of me, which, The surgeon assured me, was already firmly established.
-- The surgeon therefore set out for the dwellingplace of my friend, with a letter of introduction from me; and being received with all the civility and kindness I expected, returned to the ship's company, not only satisfied with my character, beyond the power of doubt or insinuation, but also charmed with the affability and conversation of Thomson, who loaded my character and me with presents of fresh stock, liquors and fruit.
As The surgeon would not venture to come and see us on board, left Crampley should know and detain The surgeon, when the time of us departure approached, I obtained leave to go and bid The surgeon farewell.
-- After us had vowed an everlasting friendship, The surgeon pressed upon me a purse with four double dubloons, which I refused as long as I could, without giving umbrage; and having cordially embraced each other, I returned on board, where I found a small box, with a letter directed for me, to the care of Mr. Tomlins.
-- Knowing the superscription to be of Thomson's handwriting, I opened the superscription with some surprise, and learned that this generous friend, not contented with loading me with the presents already mentioned, had sent for my use and acceptance, half a dozen fine shirts, and as many linen waistcoats and caps, with twelve pair of new thread-stockings.
-- Being thus provided with money, and all necessaries for the comfort of life, I began to look upon me as a gentleman of some consequence, and felt my pride dilate apace.
Next day us sailed for Port Royal, where us arrived safely with us prizes; and as there was nothing to do on board, I went ashore, and having purchased a laced waistcoat, with some other clothes at a vendue, made a swaggering figure for some days, among the taverns, where I ventured to play a little at hazard, and came off with fifty pistoles in my pocket.
Mean while us captain was promoted to a ship of twenty guns, and the command of the Lizzard given to a man turned of fourscore, who had been lieutenant since the reign of king William to this time, and notwithstanding our captain long service, would have probably died in that station, had our captain not employed some prize-money our captain had lately received, to make interest with our captain superiors.
